Whenever I speak in public — and it doesn’t really matter what I say — immediately comes an abusive flood of social media harassment with calls for impeachment, condemnation of the center’s politics and calls that I shouldn’t be in the Labour Party.
And it's not just my experience.
In fact, I know I’m luckier than many of my colleagues, because the comments they make to me tend to be political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who face a flurry of racist abuse every day but never back down.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era in politics is how levels of abuse have become routine.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should cultivate a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are already in the same pluralistic place, and with every decision to “distrust” or change the rules of the election, the party becomes narrower.
Over the past two years, many have advised me to keep my mouth shut, not to be so loud, and then I’ll be fine.
But that's not why I went into politics.
Ever since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a schoolboy, irritated by the Thatcher government’s neglect that has caused my public school class to almost fall apart, I’ve been looking for how to fight for better social services for those who need them most – whether as a local councillor or as a government minister.
I've never concealed my political views, including in the last election.
No one in East Nottingham could in any way be confused as to my political positions and issues of disagreement with the current leadership.
For those who pushed Friday’s decision, all I have to say is that while the country is crawling towards a Brexit that will hurt our families, our businesses and our public service, I don’t understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But in truth, the one message I have is not for momentum in Nottingham, but for my constituents, whether they are members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that no amount of threats of impeachment or political utilitarianism will deter me from acting in a way that I believe serves the best interests of all of you.
