John Edwards: Language skills are essential for the world’s citizens
The independent schools in Scotland maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this continues in 2018 with another set of outstanding test results, reinforced by individual and group success in sport, art, music and other areas of the community.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aspire to prepare their students for further and higher education, for the careers they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector that is able to design and implement a customized curriculum, we find that modern languages continue to gain popularity as a desired field of study in school.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it goes into his head.
When you speak to a man in his own language, it goes into his heart.”
It’s an important reminder that we can’t rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of the last tests this year, you can see that languages are at the top of the charts with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high A score.
Data collected from 74 schools that were members of SCIS showed that 72 percent of students achieved a high A score in Mandarin, as did 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish.
These figures show that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and adolescents will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today the field of languages as a subject of choice is considered at the same level as STEM subjects (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the British Council on Employment and Skills found that among the reasons employers cited Cody for filling vacancies, 17 percent were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Thus, to an increasing degree, language skills become an essential need to prepare students for future careers.
Given the rising demands for languages for future job opportunities, these skills are essential in the world of globalization.
No matter what career a person chooses, if they learn a second language, they will have a significant advantage in the future thanks to this lifelong ability.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically stabilizes a person in an advantageous position over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language at a level sufficient to have a conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit number of speakers, 15 percent.
That’s why it’s important to invest today in teaching children languages.
Knowledge of many languages, especially those of developing countries, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages it is taught.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will learn languages that are considered most important for Britain looking ahead to the 1920s, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever the child’s area of interest, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from in the independent schools, with a team of teachers specializing in the field.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed in any foreseeable future.
It cannot be denied today, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this fact should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be seen as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer these levels of choice, diversity and excellence to the children of Scotland.
That's the order of the hour.
John Edwards is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
